title: Investigation of the Mg-24(a,g)Si-28 reaction and of some Al-27(p,g)Si-28 resonances.

x4freetext: Investigation of the Mg-24(a,g)Si-28 reaction and of
some Al-27(p,g)Si-28 resonances.
The current, varying between 3 and
8 microA, was largest at the higher energies.
NaI scintillation crystals were 10 cm long and
10 cm in diameter.
REACTION code in Sub 002,007 were changed,
COMMON in Sub 002,007 were added. Sample description in
Sub 002-004 was corrected.
Singly charged helium ions.
Targets have been used of natural magnesium, and of
enriched Mg-24, both evaporated onto copper backings.
Three different targets were used for different alpha
energy ranges. For E < 3.1 MeV an enriched Mg-24
target of 15 mu-g/cm2 was used; for E > 3.1 Mev the
target was natural Mg of 5 mu-g/cm2 thickness; in the
energy range of approximately from 2.7 Mev to 2.93 MeV
a natural Mg target of about 3 mu-g/cm2 thickness was
used.
NaI crystal was used to detect high-energy
gamma radiation. It was placed as close to the target
as possible.
Alpha particle energy was determined with 90 degree
deflecting magnet, in which the orbit radius amounted
to 31 cm. The magnetic field was measured with a Li-7
magnetic resonance fluxmeter.
400-channel pulse analyser

The data obtained from the 24Mg(a,g)28Si reaction were
compared with the information from the 27Al(p,g)28Si
and 27Al(p,a)24Mg reactions. From the measured yields
of these three reactions, the partial widths for a, p
and g are computed for the most resonance levels.

x4code.headerHelp: Error in value of quantity, defined under ERR-ANALYS

x4freetext: The errors assigned to the (a,g) resonance
energies are compounded from:
a) the contribution, proportional to Ea, resulting
from the error in the calibration energy;
b) the error, also taken proportional to Ea, in the
determination of the low-energy edge of a resonance
peak;
c)the estimated error due to magnet saturation.
The errors in resonance strength might amount to 30%
at the strong resonances, and up to a factor of two at
the weakest resonances.

x4freetext: Singly charged helium ions.
Targets have been used of natural magnesium, and of
enriched 24Mg, both evaporated onto copper backings.
Two NaI scintillation crystals were 10 cm long
and 10 cm in diameter. Four standard geometries have
been used, indicated as I,II,V and VI. One counter
rotates in a horizontal plane at angles between 0
degree and 90 degrees with the alpha particle beam.
The beam being assumed to come horizontally. The
other counter is fixed perpendicular to the beam,
either in the horizontal plane (geometries I and II),
or vertically above the target (geometries V and VI).
In geometries I and V the first gamma ray of the
cascade is detected in the rotating counter, in
geometries II and VI it is detected in the fixed
counter.
Normalization from least-sqaures analysis.Background
was negligible.
The coincidence resolving time was 1 microsec.
Detector geometry II was used. Distance between
target and front of both crystals D was equal to 10 cm.
Detector geometry II was used. Distance between
target and the rotating counter D was equal to 5 cm,
distance between target and the fixed counter was
equal to 10 cm.
Detector geometry VI was used. Distance between
target and the fixed counter D was equal to 5 cm,
distance between target and the rotating counter was
equal to 10 cm.
Detector geometry II was used. Distance between
target and the fixed counter D was equal to 5 cm,
distance between target and the rotating counter was
equal to 10 cm.
Detector geometry I was used. Distance between
target and the fixed counter D was equal to 5 cm,
distance between target and the rotating counter was
equal to 10 cm.
Initial abscissa data are given in COS**2.
Angular correlations of the cascade through 28Si.
ANG1 is for the gamma detected in the fixed counter,
ANG2 is for the gamma detected in the rotating counter.
ANG2 is given in COS. The way of gamma detection is
defined by geometry.
